05352nam a22007095i 9781501748721DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017487217 a10.7591/97815017487212doi  a(DE-B1597)537372  a(OCoLC)1108787663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0110002bisacsh  aHI 1161qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/49786:1 aShahani, Gitanjali G., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTasting Difference :bFood, Race, and Cultural Encounters in Early Modern Literature /cGitanjali G. Shahani. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (222 p.) :b7 b&w halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Spices: “The Spicèd Indian Air” in Shakespeare’s England -- t2. Sugar: “So Sweet Was Ne’er So Fatal” -- t3. Coffee: Eating Othello, Drinking Coffee -- t4. Bizarre Foods: Food, Filth, and the Foreign in the Culinary Contact Zone -- t5. Cannibal Foods: “Powdered Wife” and Other Tales of English Cannibalism -- tCoda: Global Foods -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTasting Difference examines early modern discourses of racial, cultural, and religious difference that emerged in wake of contact with foreign peoples and exotic foods from across the globe. Gitanjali Shahani reimagines the contact zone between Western Europe and the Global South in culinary terms, emphasizing the gut rather than the gaze in colonial encounters. From household manuals that instructed English housewives how to use newly inported foodstuffs, to "the spiced Indian air" of Midsummer Night's Dream, to the repurposing of Othello as an early modern pitchman for coffee in ballads, to the performance of disgust in travel narratives, Shahani shows how early modern genres negotiated the allure and danger of foreign tastes.Turning maxims such as, "we are what we eat" on their head, Shahani asks how did we (the colonized subjects), become what you (the colonizing subjects) eat? How did we become alternately the object of fear and appetite, loathing and craving? Seeking answers to these questions, Shahani takes us back several centuries, to the process by which food came to be inscribed with racial character and the racial other came to be marked as edible, showing how the racializing of food began in an era well before chicken tikka masala and balti cuisine.Bringing into conversation critical paradigms in early modern studies, food studies, and postcolonial studies. she argues that it is in the writing on food and eating that we see among the earliest configurations of racial difference and it is experienced both as a different taste and as a taste of difference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aColonies in literature. 0aCultural relations in literature. 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aFood habits in literature. 0aFood in literature. 0aRace in literature. 0aRace relations in literature. 4aFood Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aFood history, Shakespeare, Race, Colonialism, Contact zone, Cross-cultural encounters.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2020 Englishz97